### Reactions

Despite the preceding tensions, [Russian president](/Russian_president) [Vladimir Putin](/Vladimir_Putin) acknowledged the election results and recognized Poroshenko as the legitimate president. This was a significant diplomatic move, given Russia's earlier stance.

The leaders of the [self-proclaimed](/Self-proclaimed) [Donetsk People's Republic](/Donetsk_People%27s_Republic) and [Luhansk People's Republic](/Luhansk_People%27s_Republic), however, declared that the regions had already made their choice in their own highly disputed referendums held on May 11.

On the international front, [US president](/US_president) [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama) congratulated Poroshenko via telephone two days after the election. Similar congratulations poured in from leaders of the [European Union](/EU), including [President of the European Commission](/President_of_the_European_Commission) [José Manuel Barroso](/Jos%C3%A9_Manuel_Barroso), [European Parliament President](/President_of_the_European_Parliament) [Martin Schulz](/Martin_Schulz), [German chancellor](/German_chancellor) [Angela Merkel](/Angela_Merkel), and [French president](/French_president) [François Hollande](/Fran%C3%A7ois_Hollande). It was a clear signal of international endorsement for the new leadership in Ukraine.

### Notes

*   The territorial status of [Crimea](/Crimea) and [Sevastopol](/Sevastopol) remained a point of contention. Ukraine and most of the international community recognized it as Ukrainian territory, while Russia asserted its federal subject status.
*   The Ukrainian Constitution allows for a maximum of two five-year presidential terms. However, a 2003 ruling by the [Constitutional Court of Ukraine](/Constitutional_Court_of_Ukraine) had previously permitted a third term for [Leonid Kuchma](/Leonid_Kuchma), though he ultimately declined to run.
*   Yanukovych had suspended his membership in the [Party of Regions](/Party_of_Regions) after the [2010 Ukrainian presidential election](/2010_Ukrainian_presidential_election).
*   The voter distribution in the [Donetsk Oblast](/Donetsk_Oblast) and [Luhansk Oblast](/Luhansk_Oblast) represented a significant portion of the total electorate. The absence of voting in [Crimea](/Crimea) due to its annexation further impacted the overall figures.
*   The turnout in the second round of the [2010 presidential election](/2010_presidential_election) was notably higher, with 25.5 million Ukrainians participating.
*   In some western parts of Donetsk Oblast, where paramilitary groups managed to suppress separatist activity, the election proceeded more normally.
*   Reports from the [Committee of Voters of Ukraine](/Committee_of_Voters_of_Ukraine) painted a grim picture of election committees operating "underground" amidst kidnappings and threats in the Donbas.